<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900803-0053</DOCNO><DOCID>900803-0053.</DOCID><HL>   Delta Air, Pilots Agree   On New Contract Terms   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>08/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   DAL LABOR</CO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   Delta Air Lines reached an agreement on a new contractwith its pilots that will make them the most highly paid inthe airline industry, a union official said.   The agreement, which still must be ratified by Delta unionleaders, shortens to three years the length of time newpilots are paid at lower wages than higher-seniority pilots.That hotly contested issue had been the main sticking pointin contract talks, which had dragged on for 19 months.</LP><TEXT>   The proposed contract also calls for wage increases of12.5% over its three years, with newer pilots receiving onaverage a 40% increase over the life of the contract.   A spokesman for the airline said Delta was pleased toreach an agreement, but declined further comment.   Officials of the pilots union said they were satisfiedwith the new terms. &quot;We have the best contract in theindustry,&quot; said a union spokesman. The union hailed thecontract as a significant step toward eliminating the lower&quot;B-scale.&quot; Previously, pilots had to work at the lower wagerate for five years before jumping to the higher wages ineffect for pilots with more seniority.</TEXT></DOC>